{{Corporal punishment}}

'''Cropping''' is the removal of a person's [[ear]]s as an act of physical punishment.<ref>{{harvtxt|Stronghold Knights|2010}}</ref>  It was performed along with the [[pillory]]ing or immobilisation in the [[stocks]],<ref name="Warner">{{harvtxt|Warner|2005|p=244}}</ref><ref name="Corlew163">{{harvtxt|Corlew|Folmsbee|Mitchell|1990|p=163}}</ref> and sometimes alongside punishments such as [[human branding#As punishment|branding]] or fines.<ref name="Warner" />  The punishment is described in [[Victor Hugo]]'s ''[[The Hunchback of Notre-Dame]]''.<ref name="Hugo">{{harvtxt|Hugo|1831|p=139}}</ref>

== Description ==
Cropping sometimes occurred as a standalone punishment (such as in the case of [[William Prynne]] for [[seditious libel]]),<ref name="DuCane">{{harvtxt|Du Cane|2005|p=13}}</ref> where criminals' ears would be cut off with a [[blade]].  Cropping was also a secondary punishment to having criminals' ears nailed to the pillory (with the intention that their body movements would tear them off).<ref name="DuCane" />  In 1538 [[Thomas Barrie]] spent a whole day with his ears nailed to the pillory in [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]], England, before having them cut off to release him.<ref name="Ford">{{harvtxt|Ford|2001}}</ref>

== History ==
Cropping is mentioned in ancient [[Assyrian law]] and the Babylonian [[Code of Hammurabi]].

Cropping was quite rare in [[England]], but more common in [[Guernsey]].<ref name="Ogier14">{{harvtxt|Ogier|1996|p=14}}</ref> Notable cases of cropping in England include [[Thomas Barrie]] in 1538, who reputedly died from [[Acute stress reaction|shock]] following his cropping,<ref name="Ford" /> and [[John Bastwick]], [[William Prynne]], and [[Henry Burton (Puritan)|Henry Burton]] in 1637.<ref name="Dearmer">{{harvtxt|Dearmer|2009|p=189}}</ref> In the 16th century, Henry VIII amended the laws on [[Vagrancy (people)|vagrancy]] to decree that first offences would be punished with three days in the stocks, second offences with cropping, and third offences with [[hanging]].<ref name="Adams">{{harvtxt|Adams|1998|p=41}}</ref>

Records show that croppings took place in the [[United States]] in the late 18th century, particularly in states such as [[Pennsylvania]]<ref name="Warner" /> and [[Tennessee]].<ref name="Corlew163" />

From page 153 of Reverend Samuel Peters’, General History of Connecticut, during the colonial period we have this account:

“Newhaven is celebrated for giving the name of “Pumpkin Heads” to all of New Englanders. It originated from the “Blue Laws” which enjoined every male to have his hair cut round by a cap. When caps are not to be had, they substituted a hard shell of a pumpkin, which being put on the head every Saturday, the hair is cut by the shell all round the head…….. and fourthly, such persons as have lost their ears for heresy, and other wickedness, cannot conceal their misfortune and disgrace.”

In [[Rhode Island]], cropping was a punishment for crimes such as [[Counterfeit money|counterfeiting money]], [[perjury]], and "burning houses, barns, and outbuildings" (but not amounting to [[arson]]).<ref name="PDS">{{harvtxt|Prison Discipline Society|1826|p=19}}</ref> Cropping (along with the pillory and stocks) was abolished in Tennessee in 1829, with abolition further afield starting from approximately 1839.<ref name="Kellaway">{{Harvtxt|Kellaway|2003|p=64}}</ref>

