'''Pitchipoi''' is the imaginary place where displaced Jews in France believed they would be deported to, while they were interned in the [[Drancy internment camp]] awaiting transport to [[Auschwitz]]. [[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-B10919, Frankreich, Internierungslager Drancy.jpg|right|thumb|220px|View of the accommodation block at [[Drancy internment camp]] with French [[gendarme]] on guard]] [[Image:Charlotte Salomon painting in the garden about 1939.jpg|left|thumb|200px|[[Charlotte Salomon]] painting in her garden about 1939]] In her biography of the painter [[Charlotte Salomon]], who was transported from Drancy to Auschwitz in September 1943, Mary Felstiner quotes from the testimony of [[Holocaust]] survivors the following points:
For some, Pitchipoi was the nonsense name of a Polish ghetto, a [[Yiddish]] name used by Polish Jews; for some, the word "resonated like an eternal curse"; for others, "Pitchipoi was a place of compulsory forced labor".<ref>Felstiner, 1994, ''To Paint Her Life'', pp. 197–199.</ref>
It was [[Nazi]] policy to keep Jewish prisoners in a state of ignorance about their final destination, so Pitchipoi was invented to fill this vacuum in their knowledge. Most prisoners were murdered on arrival at the [[death camp]]s organised by the Germans.
